== Sockets ==
Python can also communicate via sockets.
=== Connecting to a server === This simple Python program will fetch a 4096 byte HTTP response from Google: <source lang=python> import socket, sys sock = socket.socket ( socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM ) sock.connect ( ( "google.com", 80 ) )
sock.send('GET / HTTP/1.1\r\n') sock.send('User-agent: Mozilla/5.0 (wikibooks test)\r\n\r\n') print sock.recv(4096) </source>
== High-level interfaces ==
Most Python developers will prefer to use a high-level interface over using sockets, such as [http://twistedmatrix.com/trac/ Twisted] and [http://docs.python.org/2/library/urllib2 urllib2].
